Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Afribank of Nigeria; Guaranty Trust

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-07-12T16:07:16Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-12/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-afribank-of-nigeria-guaranty-trust.html
Kenya’s All-Share Index dropped for
a sixth day, slumping 2 percent to 67.75 by the 3 p.m. close in
Nairobi, the lowest since March 2010.  The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index weakened for a
third day, falling 0.9 percent to 23,959.70 by the 2:30 p.m.
close in Lagos, according to an e-mailed statement from the
bourse. Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index slid for a third day, declining
0.5 percent to 2,079.84, the longest losing streak since the
three days through May 19, by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis .
Namibia’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  retreated for a third day,
sliding 0.2 percent to 842.34 at the 4 p.m. close in Windhoek,
the lowest level since June 28. The Ghana Stock Exchange
Composite Index fell for a fourth day, retreating less than 0.1
percent to 1,182.39 by the 3 p.m. close in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Afribank Plc (AFRIBANK NL), a Nigerian lender bailed out
two years ago by the  central bank , dropped 5 kobo, or the
maximum daily limit of 5 percent, its biggest daily decline
since June 9, to 95 kobo, after Business Day said that plans by
the private-equity firm Vine Capital Partners Ltd. to acquire
the bank have probably collapsed.  Guaranty Trust Bank Plc (GUARANTY)  ,  Nigeria ’s third-
biggest lender by market value, dropped 74 kobo, or 5 percent,
to 14.2 naira, the lowest since Dec. 24, on speculation that the
Central Bank’s plans to stabilize the banking industry may not
work by its September deadline. “People are still skeptical
over Nigeria’s banking reforms, including the deadlines for the
rescued banks,” Esili Eigbe, a Lagos-based analyst with Stanbic
IBTC Bank Plc, said by phone today.  Bank PHB Plc (PLATINUM)   a Nigerian lender rescued by
the central bank in 2009, fell 2 kobo, or 2.6 percent, to 74
kobo, the lowest level since June 21.  To contact the reporter on this story:
